##What can we learn from the outbreak at Amoy Gardens in Hong Kong 17 years ago?

I-CAIJING

CAIJING magazine official Wechat. "CAIJING" magazine, sponsored by the China Securities Market Research Center, was first published in 1998, adhering to the news concept of "independence, exclusiveness and originality" , and is known for authoritative, impartial and professional reporting, it is a must-read publication for policy-makers, researchers and managers in the field of politics and economics.

Since fighting SARS in 2003, whenever new diseases appear, Hong Kong people always think of Amoy Garden. The social reality involved in this symbolic building is still meaningful for understanding the pressure of the current epidemic prevention system in the Hong Kong SAR

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In early February, the Food and Environmental Hygiene Department began putting up posters in Hong Kong.

By Jiao Jian, CAIJING correspondent

Editor | Susie

Around the Chinese New Year, the COVID-19 epidemic spread from mainland China to Hong Kong, China. In Hong Kong, the price of face masks, vegetables, rice and meat has risen or been cut off due to a citywide buying spree. Bleach used for disinfection is also in short supply in many outlets.

It is mainly used in the u-shaped cistern / Water Collector (called "water storage bend" in the mainland) which is diluted by Hong Kong people and poured into family toilets. The fear in Hong Kong is that COVID-19 can be transmitted through faeces, and preparations must be made to prevent a return to the u-shaped trough in Amoy Gardens when the SARS outbreak 17 years ago turned into a channel for spreading the virus.

A number of friends familiar to the reporter from Caijing, who live in Shenzhen and Hong Kong, have recently started to share relevant experience: for Prevention (especially for patients in the same district) , one can use 1:49 of bleach or disinfectant mixed with cold water, pour some into all sinks (including floor drains) every morning and evening to keep the u-shaped sink hydrated and virus isolated.

Because there are so many such cases, the director of the Centre for infection and infectious diseases of the University of Hong Kong, Ho Pak-leung, recently launched the Hoo Hoo campaign, saying: "Wash hands regularly with soap and water, and always cover the toilet plate before flushing. In addition, pouring water into the U-SHAPED channel every day is believed to prevent the spread of the virus. Do Not pour bleach, as it will cause serious environmental pollution."

On February 1, the Shenzhen Third People's Hospital revealed that 2019-nCoV nucleic acid (COVID-19) was positive in the faeces of patients with certain COVID-19 pneumonia, possibly indicating the presence of live virus in the faeces, china's Ministry of Ecology and Environment has also issued relevant documents, arranged the deployment of medical sewage and urban sewage supervision, and standardized the requirements for emergency treatment and disinfection of medical sewage, so as to prevent the spread of COVID-19 through feces and sewage.

U-FLUME hidden risk

Let Hong Kong people every time the epidemic period will be snapped up mask and disinfection water source, is 2003 SARS as one of the major disaster areas Amoy Garden can be described as "epidemic" experience:

Amoy Gardens is a large private residential complex in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region. It is located in Ngau Tau Kok, Kwun Tong, Kowloon. The estate was built from 1980 to 1987 and was occupied in 1981.

In February 2003, a professor surnamed Liu went to Hong Kong with his wife to attend his nephew's wedding banquet on the 21st of the same month after he took antibiotics to improve his condition after showing symptoms of pneumonia (which was actually SARS) , after checking into the hotel, 16 hotel guests and visitors were infected. A 26-year-old Hong Kong resident, who had visited a hotel where he stayed, developed fever and attended the Prince of Wales Hospital on 28th. He was diagnosed as respiratory tract infection and discharged home. He returned to the accident and emergency department on March 4 and was admitted to ward 8A, causing a number of patients in the ward to be infected.

For Amoy Gardens, which came to be known as the site of the Severe Acute Respiratory System Syndrome outbreak, the source patient was a 33-year-old man who frequently visited his brother in Amoy Gardens, according to the investigation by the Department of Health of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) . The patient suffers from chronic kidney disease disease and has been receiving treatment at Prince of Wales Hospital. In March 2003, he presented with severe symptoms. However, on 14 March and 19 March, he visited a unit owned by his brother in Block E of Amoy Garden and used the toilet of the unit due to diarrhea. Subsequently, his younger brother, his wife and two nurses who were caring for him at the Prince of Wales Hospital confirmed that they were infected with Severe Acute Respiratory System Syndrome.

As at 15 April 2003, there were 321 cases of Severe Acute Respiratory System Syndrome in Amoy Gardens. The number of cases was significantly concentrated in block e, accounting for 41% of the cumulative total.

"The noise started at four or five in the morning. When I turned on the surveillance cameras, there were people wearing white clothes and wearing masks outside. The Gate was sealed, the whole building could not leave, and all the residents moved into the isolation camp. Those with infected family members will go to the lady maclehose resort for observation, while those without symptoms will go to the Lyemun Barracks,"a resident who lived through the period told Caijing.

Block E, like the other blocks in Amoy Gardens, is a 33-storey building with eight flats on each floor. Each building has eight vertical sewers to collect sewage. This sewage pipe connects the floor drains of the water closet, sink, bathtub and bathroom, each with a u-shaped water collector.

According to a joint investigation conducted by various official bodies in the Hong Kong SAR of China, the u-shaped water collector connected to the toilet and bathtub has water most of the time and acts as a barrier due to frequent use. However, the u-shaped water collector connected to the floor drain may fail to act as an isolation due to the fact that most households use mops instead of water to clean the bathroom floor. According to the investigation, when the bathroom fan is activated, the air will flow back from the sewage pipe through the floor drain into the bathroom. It is speculated that these air currents may distribute the virus-carrying fluids stored in the sewer pipes indoors and discharge them to the Patios of the adjacent units, and eventually enter the adjacent homes through the windows.

Thus, Amoy Gardens has a relatively complete chain of infection: the source patient may first pass through the sewage drainage system in block E, person-to-person contact, and the building's public facilities (elevators and stairs) , that infected a group of residents in the building, and then infected other residents in the same building. It may then spread the virus to residents inside and outside block e through person-to-person contact and contaminated environmental facilities.

After Amoy Gardens, to avoid similar incidents, the Hong Kong SAR Government of China has formulated guidelines to educate the public on how to disinfect their homes, this includes how to clean the bathroom and maintain the air isolation of the U-SHAPED trap (households should pour about half a litre of fresh water into the outfall at least once a week to ensure that the u-shaped trap or trap is maintained) . Guidelines have also been issued to remind the public of the importance of proper maintenance and repair of drainage systems and sanitary facilities. The guidelines have been distributed to property management companies and owners'corporations (similar to the business committees in the mainland) . Relevant information can also be found on the relevant government websites.

Even more striking is the fact that the lift buttons in many residential and commercial buildings have been covered with transparent plastic film and re-labelled every two hours following the confirmation of COVID-19 cases in Hong Kong.

New Pressure on epidemic prevention this year

##

The intangible institutional experience is relatively easy to sort out and summarize. However, the objective reality of "more people, fewer houses" that has not been solved in Hong Kong since 2003 has caused many people in Hong Kong to worry about the pressure of epidemic prevention in the face of various new viruses.

Take Amoy Garden as an example: Because of the high living density, the bathroom area is very small (about 3.5 square meters) , whenever someone uses the bathroom, the closed door and the running exhaust fan can cause a strong negative air pressure, small droplets of the virus are driven through a floor drain into the bathroom and are then attached to surfaces such as carpets, towels and toilet articles.

"So when a new building is built or renovated, the sewer system must meet the requirements and be fitted with a 'back siphonage valve' to avoid sucking water from the u-shaped water collector and increasing the risk of bacteria entering the building, " a property manager in Hong Kong told Caijing, "So the average family is fine, but there are more families out there. "

The pressure of living with more people and less land has also resulted in the existence of a large number of families living in "sub-divided units" in Hong Kong over the years. Over the past decade or so, due to various constraints, the total number of sub-divided units in old buildings in the densely populated urban areas of Hong Kong has increased steadily compared with that in 2003. According to the 2016 population by-census of the Census and Statistics Department, Hong Kong, China, there are about 92,700 sub-divided units in Hong Kong, housing nearly 210,000 people, with an average of 3.4 sub-divided units per unit.

A person who was the chairman of the "anti-inflammatory Task Force" of the Hong Kong institution of Engineers (hkie) in 2003 said many years ago that some sub-divided units needed to be raised to provide separate kitchen and toilet units, or were involved in unauthorised alterations, it is difficult to guarantee the compliance of the plumbing system and the installation of u-shaped water traps. Some toilets in sub-divided units do not have windows, which may increase the risk of spreading the virus under poor ventilation.

Wu Manhai, a former director of buildings of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region government who was involved in the SARS outbreak at Amoy Gardens, said, "the biggest problem is sub-divided units that are not up to standard and how the government follows up on the drainage system of such sub-divided units. ".

Apart from sub-divided units, the "chimney effect" produced by the high-density design of high-rise buildings and what impact the high-density crowd gathering in Hong Kong will have on the fight against the epidemic, it is also becoming a matter of concern for all concerned in Hong Kong: Based on population density, not just circulation, the epidemic in Hong Kong is likely to be more severe than in the north, the upper, the deep, the broad and even Chongqing.

In terms of population density, Hong Kong has one of the highest population densities in the world. According to the 2018 land area of Hong Kong by District Council district, the 2018 population by-year and population density statistics (revised as at 4 March 2019) showed that the total land population in Hong Kong was 6890 persons per square kilometre.

As many areas in Hong Kong are sites for conservation or Brownfield sites which are difficult to use, "Hong Kong has a population of more than seven million, and currently lives in a 267-square-kilometer area, with an average population density of 27,000 people per square kilometer... only Dhaka in Bangladesh and Mumbai in India have the same population density as Hong Kong, " the former Secretary for development of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region government said in a previous blog post.

From the end of January to the present, Caijing reporter in Hong Kong SAR several popular shopping district interview found: Although public libraries, swimming pools and other public facilities have been temporarily closed. A large number of pedestrians have also been wearing masks of different specifications, but the business of shopping and catering shops is still relatively prosperous.

As of 12:00 noon on February 2, the latest statistics show that the number of confirmed cases in the COVID-19 in Hong Kong, China is 14, with no deaths and no cured cases of discharge. The pressure of epidemic prevention remains, but the situation has not worsened.
